The start symbol S has only two possibilities:

1. S → NT8 NT19      
2. S → NT20 NT47

Hence the string must be split into two contiguous parts whose lengths sum to 20, so that

• the first part is derived from NT8 or NT20, and  
• the second part is derived from NT19 or NT47 respectively.

Look at the last token of the string, t9.

─  If we use rule (2) (S → NT20 NT47), the suffix (produced by NT47) would have to yield a string ending in t9.  
   The only multi-token productions for NT47 are
      NT47 → NT17 NT23   (NT23 is last) and  
      NT47 → NT49 NT20   (NT20 gives the tail).

   • In the first case the last token comes from NT23, but NT23 can only produce t6, t12 or t49 – never t9.  
   • In the second case the first token of the suffix must be supplied by NT49, but NT49 only produces t17, t59, t66 or t69 – none of which occurs after position 8 of our string.  

   Therefore NT47 cannot generate any suffix that ends with t9, so rule (2) is impossible.

─  If we use rule (1) (S → NT8 NT19), the suffix is produced by NT19.  
   NT19 can terminate only with a single terminal t5 or t68, or with NT15 (via NT19 → NT19 NT15) or with NT33 (via NT19 → NT42 NT33).  
   NT15 can give t19, t21, t34, t58 or t61; NT33 can give t56 or t64.  
   None of these possibilities is t9, so NT19 can never produce a string whose last symbol is t9.

Hence neither of the two mandatory suffix generators (NT47 or NT19) can yield a string ending in t9. Since our target string ends in t9, it cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The last token of the string is “t52”.  
In the grammar the only production that yields the terminal “t52” is

  NT10 → 't52'

Hence the right-most leaf of any derivation of the string must be produced by NT10.

Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form, NT10 must be the second (right-hand) child of some binary production X → Y NT10; otherwise the tokens generated by NT10 would not be the right-most ones in the string.  
Scanning the grammar, the only rule where NT10 appears in second position is

  NT44 → NT18 NT10.

Therefore the last two contiguous blocks of terminals in any derivation must be
 • a block generated by NT18, followed immediately by  
 • the single terminal “t52” generated by NT10.

In the given string the terminal that immediately precedes “t52” is “t63”.  
So NT18 would have to generate a sequence ending in “t63”.

But NT18 can produce only
 't54', 't29', 't4', 't23', or (via NT18 → NT49 NT7) combinations of the terminals
 { 't17', 't59', 't66', 't69' } from NT49 followed by { 't45', 't49', 't31' } from NT7.

The terminal “t63” is not contained in any of these sets, nor can it be produced
by NT18 through any chain of productions (NT18 never derives a non-terminal that
can yield “t63”).

Consequently NT18 cannot generate a sequence whose last symbol is “t63”, and
there is no way for the grammar to place “t52” at the end of the string.

Hence the given string cannot be derived from the start symbol S.

No

To end with the terminal t1 the derivation must ultimately reach the non-terminal NT44, because NT44 is the only symbol in the grammar that has a terminal production for t1 (NT44 → 't1').

Consequently, the last two terminals of any word that the grammar can produce have to originate from a rule whose right-hand side ends with NT44.  
Looking through all binary rules (the grammar is in CNF), every rule whose second symbol is NT44 is one of the following:

  • NT14  → NT41 NT44  
  • NT33  → NT41 NT44  
  • NT43  → NT27 NT44  
  • NT46  → NT6  NT44  
  • NT1   → NT44 NT7   (NT44 is first, not second)  

For any of these rules, the token immediately before the final t1 must come from NT41, NT27, NT6, or NT44 itself.

Now check which terminals those non-terminals can produce:

  • NT41 → 't3'  
  • NT27 ends with NT24 and therefore can only end in t24, t73, t5, t44, t41, t46, etc., never t60.  
  • NT6  → 't50' | 't33' | 't64' | 't16' (and nothing else ending in t60)  
  • NT44 → 't1'

Thus no derivation that places NT44 at the end can produce the pair t60 t1 as the final two terminals; the token preceding t1 can never be t60.

Since the given string ends with “… t60 t1”, no non-terminal of the grammar can derive that suffix, and therefore the start symbol S cannot derive the entire string.

No

The start symbol S has only two possibilities in this grammar  

 1. S → NT8 NT19  
 2. S → NT20 NT47  

For the 21-token string we must therefore be able to split the string into  

 (prefix) ⊕ (suffix) = (value of the left child) ⊕ (value of the right child)  

according to one of the rules above.

----------------------------------------------------------------
1.  Trying S → NT8 NT19
----------------------------------------------------------------
NT19 can generate  

 • the single terminal ‘t5’ or ‘t68’, or  
 • a string that ends with one of those terminals via the only binary rule  
  NT19 → NT19 NT15.

In the given string the ONLY occurrence of ‘t5’ or ‘t68’ is the single ‘t5’ situated at position 20  
( the last two tokens are “… t5 t34” ).  
Consequently the shortest suffix NT19 could possibly cover is either

 (a) just token 20 (“t5”), or  
 (b) the two–token block “t5 t34” (via NT19 → NT19 NT15).

In both cases NT19’s part ends with “t5”.  
That means all tokens situated strictly before “t5” (i.e. positions 1 – 19) would have to be generated by the non-terminal NT8.

But NT8 itself has only three rules

 NT8 → ‘t69’    　(length 1)  
 NT8 → ‘t70’    　(length 1)  
 NT8 → NT20 NT9  　(length ≥ 2)

Because the prefix contains 19 tokens, NT8 must expand through the binary rule NT8 → NT20 NT9.

Hence the 19-token prefix must split into  

 (prefix-1) produced by NT20  followed by  (prefix-2) produced by NT9.

Now examine NT9.  It can be obtained only as

 NT9 → ‘t2’  
 NT9 → NT45 NT18  (ends with an NT18)  
 NT9 → NT11 NT19  (ends with an NT19)

Therefore every string produced by NT9 necessarily ends with one of the terminals

 ‘t2’, ‘t4’, ‘t23’, ‘t29’, ‘t54’, ‘t5’ or ‘t68’.

Look at the last symbol of the 19-token prefix (token #19): it is “t19”, which is NOT in that list.  
Hence the 19-token prefix cannot be derived from NT9 – and consequently cannot be derived from NT8.  
Thus S → NT8 NT19 is impossible.

----------------------------------------------------------------
2.  Trying S → NT20 NT47
----------------------------------------------------------------
The right child here is NT47.  
NT47 has only the following possibilities:

 NT47 → ‘t8’    　　　 (single token)  
 NT47 → ‘t72’   　　　 (single token)  
 NT47 → NT17 NT23  
 NT47 → NT49 NT20

In every expansion except the single-terminal cases the **rightmost** symbol of the substring
generated by NT47 is produced by either NT23 or NT20.

The final token of the whole string is “t34”.  
Check whether NT23 or NT20 can ever yield “t34”:

• NT23 has only  
 NT23 → ‘t12’ | ‘t6’ | ‘t49’ | NT14 NT3.  
NT14 can generate ‘t59’ or ‘t74’; NT3 can generate ‘t50’, ‘t39’, or ‘t35’.  
None of these gives ‘t34’.  So NT23 can never end with ‘t34’.

• NT20’s own terminals are ‘t57’, ‘t63’, ‘t49’, ‘t37’, ‘t73’, ‘t23’, ‘t35’, ‘t38’ – again never ‘t34’.  
Its binary rules always delegate the rightmost token to some other non-terminal, but every possible
chain ultimately yields one of the terminals just listed, never ‘t34’.

Therefore no derivation of NT47 can terminate with the token “t34”, so the suffix of our string
cannot be generated by NT47.  Hence S → NT20 NT47 is also impossible.

----------------------------------------------------------------
Since both alternatives for the start symbol S are ruled out, the given
grammar cannot generate the string.
